  "text": "## Health Endpoint Implementation Comparison Across Three Major Go Projects\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nKubernetes implements a sophisticated health checking system with three distinct endpoints:\n\n**Endpoints:** `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`\n\n**Key Files:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go` - Core health check framework defining the `HealthChecker` interface with `Name()` and `Check(req *http.Request) error` methods\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go` - GenericAPIServer integration with health check registries\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/etcd.go` - Database-specific health checks\n\n**Key Symbols:**\n- `InstallHandler()`, `InstallReadyzHandler()`, `InstallLivezHandler()` - Registration functions for endpoints\n- `HealthChecker` interface - Pluggable health check implementation\n- Built-in checks: `PingHealthz` (always returns ok), `LogHealthz` (verifies logging not blocked), `NewInformerSyncHealthz()` (checks informer cache sync), `NewShutdownHealthz()` (fails when shutdown starts)\n\n**Dependency Checks:**\n- **Database (etcd):** `CreateHealthCheck()` and `CreateReadyCheck()` from storage factory check etcd connectivity and readiness via `NamedGroupedCheck(\"etcd-readiness\", \"etcd-readiness\", ...)`\n- **Informers:** Verify all informers have synced caches\n- **Shutdown Signal:** Track graceful shutdown state\n\n**Architecture:**\nKubernetes uses a health check registry pattern where multiple checks are collected and installed via `InstallPathHandler()`. The system supports excluding checks via query parameters (`?exclude=check-name`) and verbose output (`?verbose=1`). Each registry (healthz, livez, readyz) maintains independent check lists with optional grace periods for livez during boot sequences.\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\nGrafana implements a minimal health endpoint system focused on operator readiness signaling.\n\n**Endpoints:** `/livez`, `/readyz`\n\n**Key Files:**\n- `pkg/server/health.go` - Health endpoint handlers and HealthNotifier state management\n- `pkg/services/apiserver/service.go` - Endpoint registration via gorilla/mux\n\n**Key Symbols:**\n- `HealthNotifier` struct - Thread-safe state holder using `atomic.Bool`\n- `LivezHandler()` - Always returns 200 OK (process is alive)\n- `ReadyzHandler(h *HealthNotifier)` - Returns 200 OK if ready, 503 if not ready\n- `RegisterHealthEndpoints()` - Registers both endpoints on provided router\n- `SetReady()`, `SetNotReady()`, `IsReady()` - State management methods\n\n**Dependency Checks:**\nGrafana uses a simple binary readiness state managed by operators. No automatic dependency checks for databases or caches. Instead, operators explicitly signal readiness via `SetReady()` after completing initialization.\n\n**Architecture:**\nGrafana's approach is intentionally simple: livez always succeeds (indicating the HTTP server is running), while readyz returns success only when the operator has explicitly called `SetReady()`. This allows operators to perform their own initialization checks and signal completion. The health state is shared across the InstrumentationServer and OperatorServer via a single shared `HealthNotifier` instance.\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nPrometheus implements health endpoints with TSDB readiness gating and graceful shutdown support.\n\n**Endpoints:** `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready` (note: different path prefix convention)\n\n**Key Files:**\n- `web/web.go` - Handler definition, ReadyStatus state machine, and endpoint registration\n\n**Key Symbols:**\n- `ReadyStatus` enum with three states: `NotReady` (iota = 0), `Ready` (= 1), `Stopping` (= 2)\n- `testReady()` method - Wraps handlers with readiness checks\n- `isReady()` - Returns true if ReadyStatus == Ready\n- `setReady()`, `setNotReady()`, `setStopping()` - State transition methods\n- Metrics: `prometheus_ready` gauge tracks readiness state\n\n**Dependency Checks:**\n- **TSDB Readiness:** The ready endpoint checks if TSDB (Time Series Database) has completed initialization\n- **Graceful Shutdown:** Returns 503 when in Stopping state (signaling removal from load balancers while keeping liveness checks passing)\n\n**Architecture:**\nPrometheus uses a state machine approach with three states. The `/-/healthy` endpoint (HEAD and GET support) always succeeds, while `/-/ready` (also HEAD and GET) wraps handlers with `testReady()` middleware that:\n- Returns 200 OK if Ready\n- Returns 503 Service Unavailable with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: false` if NotReady\n- Returns 503 Service Unavailable with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` if Stopping\n\nThis allows clients to distinguish between \"not yet ready\" and \"actively shutting down\" scenarios. The ready endpoint also guards API endpoints like `/federate` and `/consoles` to prevent serving traffic during startup or shutdown.\n\n### Comparison Summary\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | Grafana | Prometheus |\n|--------|-----------|---------|------------|\n| **Endpoints** | /healthz, /livez, /readyz | /livez, /readyz | /-/healthy, /-/ready |\n| **DB Checks** | Yes (etcd via NamedGroupedCheck) | No (manual) | Implicit (TSDB readiness) |\n| **Cache/Informer Checks** | Yes (NewInformerSyncHealthz) | No | No |\n| **Pluggable Checks** | Yes (HealthChecker interface) | No (binary state only) | No |\n| **Shutdown Handling** | Explicit NewShutdownHealthz | No | Stopping state with header |\n| **Grace Periods** | Yes (livez grace period) | No | No |\n| **Query Parameters** | Yes (?exclude, ?verbose) | No | No |\n\n**Common Patterns:**\n- All three separate liveness (/livez or /-/healthy) from readiness (/readyz or /-/ready)\n- Readiness checks block traffic during startup\n- Support for HTTP HEAD requests in addition to GET\n- Graceful shutdown integration (explicit in Kubernetes/Prometheus, implicit in Grafana via SetNotReady)"
}

