B Readiness:** The ready endpoint checks if TSDB (Time Series Database) has completed initialization\n- **Graceful Shutdown:** Returns 503 when in Stopping state (signaling removal from load balancers while keeping liveness checks passing)\n\n**Architecture:**\nPrometheus uses a state machine approach with three states. The `/-/healthy` endpoint (HEAD and GET support) always succeeds, while `/-/ready` (also HEAD and GET) wraps handlers with `testReady()` middleware that:\n- Returns 200 OK if Ready\n- Returns 503 Service Unavailable with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: false` if NotReady\n- Returns 503 Service Unavailable with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` if Stopping\n\nThis allows clients to distinguish between \"not yet ready\" and \"actively shutting down\" scenarios. The ready endpoint also guards API endpoints like `/federate` and `/consoles` to prevent serving traffic during startup or shutdown.\n\n### Comparison Summary\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | Grafana | Prometheus |\n|--------|-----------|---------|------------|\n| **Endpoints** | /healthz, /livez, /readyz | /livez, /readyz | /-/healthy, /-/ready |\n| **DB Checks** | Yes (etcd via NamedGroupedCheck) | No (manual) | Implicit (TSDB readiness) |\n| **Cache/Informer Checks** | Yes (NewInformerSyncHealthz) | No | No |\n| **Pluggable Checks** | Yes (HealthChecker interface) | No (binary state only) | No |\n| **Shutdown Handling** | Explicit NewShutdownHealthz | No | Stopping state with header |\n| **Grace Periods** | Yes (livez grace period) | No | No |\n| **Query Parameters** | Yes (?exclude, ?verbose) | No | No |\n\n**Common Patterns:**\n- All three separate liveness (/livez or /-/healthy) from readiness (/readyz or /-/ready)\n- Readiness checks block traffic during startup\n- Support for HTTP HEAD requests in addition to GET\n- Graceful shutdown integration (explicit in Kubernetes/Prometheus, implicit in Grafana via SetNotReady)"
